      "description": "Ovako develops high-tech steel solutions for, and in cooperation with, its customers in the bearing, transport and manufacturing industries. Ovako is a subsidiary of Sanyo Special Steel and of Nippon Steel Corporation group",
      "text_excerpt": "Ovako – Leading European Engineering Steel Manufacturer for Sustainable Solutions - Ovako\nTogether we create steel for a decarbonized society\nNordic steel meets world‑class performance – Ovako announces partnership with Daniel Ståhl\nRead more\nStories\nRead all our stories\nResearch and Insights\nResearch project leads the way to lead-free steel machining\nResearch comparing leaded and lead-free steels shows similar or better machinability, supporting the feasibility of lead-free alternatives when process parameters are managed.\nAbout Ovako\nWe are proud to be named Career Company 2026 - Again\nFor the fourth year in a row, Ovako is named one of Sweden’s most attractive employers, with focus on sustainable development, fossil-free steel and an inclusive workplace.\nCustomer case\nVETTERs  reputation is built on safety and reliability\nFor over 40 years, VETTER has trusted Ovako steel to deliver strength, safety and reliability in the toughest environments. Discover how precision materials raise fork performance worldwide.\nServices\nThe top five questions we get from customers\nBehind every steel order is more than schedules—it’s communication, flexibility, and people making things happen. With 29 yrs experience, Ulla Kaski shares the 5 top customer questions.\nEmployee Stories\nOur iron ladies: celebrating International Women’s Day at Ovako\nMeet the women shaping the future of steel. In this International Women’s Day story, Ovako colleagues share their experiences, challenges and advice from working in a traditionally male-dominated industry.\nSustainability\nHow CBAM is changing the rules for the steel industry\nThe EU’s Carbon Border Adjustment Mechanism is redefining global steelmaking. Discover how CBAM affects emissions, import costs, and what it means for steel producers like Ovako—and why cleaner, low-carbon technologies are the way forward.\nResearch and Insights\nHow lean alloy steels enable green ammonia engines\nUsing ammonia 